# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: batak-cuisine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:batak-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] Pasta, meat, and vegetables are central to the cuisine of Abruzzo.
[src:batak-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] Chili peppers (Italian: *peperoncini*) are typical of Abruzzo, where they are called *diavoletti* (lit.
[src:batak-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] Due to the long history of shepherding in Abruzzo, lamb dishes are common.
[src:batak-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] Mushrooms (usually wild mushrooms), rosemary, and garlic are also extensively used in Abruzzese cuisine.
[src:batak-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] Best-known is the extra virgin olive oil produced in the local farms on the hills of the region, marked by the quality level DOP and considered one of the best in the country.
[src:batak-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] Renowned wines such as Montepulciano DOCG and Trebbiano d'Abruzzo DOC are considered amongst the world's finest wines.
[src:batak-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] In 2012, a bottle of Trebbiano d'Abruzzo Colline Teramane ranked No.
[src:batak-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] *Centerbe* is a strong (72% alcohol), spicy herbal liqueur drunk by the locals.
[src:batak-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] Another liqueur is *genziana*, a soft distillate of gentian roots.
[src:batak-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] The best-known dish from Abruzzo is *arrosticini*, little pieces of castrated lamb on a wooden stick and cooked on coals.
[src:batak-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] 'guitar') is a variety of egg pasta, with a square cross section about 2–3 mm thick.
[src:batak-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] In the province of Teramo, famous local dishes include the *virtù* soup (made with legumes, vegetables, and pork meat), the *timballo* (pasta sheets filled with meat, vegetables or rice), and the *mazzarelle* (lamb intestines filled with garlic, marjoram, lettuce, and various spices).
[src:batak-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] The popularity of saffron, grown in the province of L'Aquila, has waned in recent years.
[src:batak-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] Seafood also plays an important role in the cuisine of Abruzzo, especially areas near the coast.
[src:batak-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] Spreadable sausage flavored with nutmeg and liver sausage with garlic and spices are hallmarks of Teramo cuisine.
[src:batak-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] *Ventricina* from the Vasto area is made with large pieces of fat and lean pork, pressed and seasoned with powdered sweet peppers and fennel and encased in dried pig stomach.
[src:batak-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] Atri and Rivisondoli are known for their cheeses.
[src:batak-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] Mozzarella (fresh or seasoned) is typically made from ewe's milk; many lesser-known cheeses are found throughout Abruzzo and Molise.
[src:batak-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] The use of oil in regional mountain and sea dishes is important; among the most common oil products we find the Aprutino Pescarese, the Pretuziano delle Colline Teramane, l'Olio extra vergine di oliva delle Valli Aquilane and Colline Teatine.
[src:batak-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] Renowned wines like Montepulciano DOCG, Terre Tollesi DOCG, Trebbiano d'Abruzzo DOC and Controguerra DOC are judged to be amongst the world's finest.
[src:batak-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] In 2012, a bottle of Trebbiano d'Abruzzo ranked No.
[src:batak-cuisine/abruzzese-cuisine] IGT wines are Alto Tirino, Colli Aprutini, Colli del Sangro, Colline Frentane, Colline Pescaresi, Colline Teatine, Del Vastese (or Histonium), Terre di Chieti, and Valle Peligna.
[src:batak-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] Acadian cuisine is not very well known in Canada or internationally.
[src:batak-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] It has much in common with Québécois cuisine because of its geographical proximity.
[src:batak-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] The two often feature the same dishes, but the cuisine of Acadia puts more emphasis on seafood.
[src:batak-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] Acadian cuisine has notably served as the base for Cajun cuisine because the Cajun are descendants of Acadians who were deported to Louisiana.Note 2 It is also believed that Acadians are responsible for normalizing potato consumption in France—a vegetable the French once considered poisonous.
[src:batak-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] In the 17th century, French colonists who settled on lands they named Acadia adapted their 16th-century French cuisine to incorporate the crops, seafood and animals that flourished in the region.
[src:batak-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] Their descendants became the Acadian people and their ingenuity created Acadian cuisine.
[src:batak-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] After the English conquered Acadia during the 18th century, they decided to deport the Acadians and take their settlements, which were often built on the most fertile earth in the colony.
[src:batak-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] Most Acadians did not manage to escape the deportation.
[src:batak-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] But, of those who did, most fled to the east and north of New BrunswickNote 3.
[src:batak-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] As such, Acadian cuisine in the 18th century was refocused around what could be grown, hunted and fished in the less fertile lands of the East Coast of New Brunswick and the Upper St.
[src:batak-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] Acadian cuisine often features fish and seafood, especially cod and Atlantic herring, but also mackerel, berlicoco, lobster, crab, salmon, mussels, trout, clams, flounder, smelt and scallops.
[src:batak-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] Most fish is consumed fresh, but some are *boucané* (smoked), marinated or salted.
[src:batak-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] The most commonly used meat is pork, followed by chicken and beef.
[src:batak-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] As with the rest of North America, turkey is commonly consumed during the holidays.
[src:batak-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] Game like deer, hare, ruffed grouse and moose is consumed regularly in some regions.
[src:batak-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] Game will replace livestock meat if present and can be given as a gift.
[src:batak-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] In some regions, for example Caraquet and the Îles-de-la-Madeleine, more unusual game is or was caught, like seal, bear and seagull.
[src:batak-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] The vegetables of Acadian cuisine are the potato, onion, carrot, turnip, legume, beet, squash and corn.
[src:batak-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] These vegetables were popular because they were easily preserved for the winter in root cellars and jars.
[src:batak-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] The fiddlehead fern was introduced to the Acadians by the indigenous Maliseet, Mi'kmaq and Penobscot peoples in the early 18th Century and remains a popular Acadian dish.
[src:batak-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] Popular fruits include blueberries, apples, strawberries, raspberries, blackberries, plums, pears and cranberries.
[src:batak-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] Some ingredients like rice, molasses, dried raisins and brown sugar are part of Acadian cuisine because of historical commerce between Acadia and regions like the Antilles and Brazil.
[src:batak-cuisine/acadian-cuisine] Maple sugar is also a popular sweetener, given the often-close familial ties between Quebec (the world's largest producer of maple sugar) and Acadia.
[src:batak-cuisine/acar] Through examining the etymology, the similar sounding name strongly suggests that indeed acar was derived from the Indian achar pickle.
[src:batak-cuisine/acar] Indian achar was transmitted in antiquity to the maritime realm of Southeast Asia, which today is recognized as acar in Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore and Brunei, and then on to the Philippines as *atchara*.
[src:batak-cuisine/acar] The adoption of this vegetable pickling technique possibly took place during the Srivijaya period between 7th to 13th century.
[src:batak-cuisine/acar] British navigator Thomas Forrest wrote that acar made of salted limes and palm vinegar was often of use to Coromandel Muslim sailors (*Chulias*) to prevent scurvy and was sold as far as Aceh.
[src:batak-cuisine/acar] The Southeast Asian variations are usually made from different vegetables such as cucumber, carrots, cabbage, shallot, bird's eye chili and yardlong beans, which are pickled in vinegar, sometimes with kaffir lime to add citrus aroma, and also dried chillies.
[src:batak-cuisine/acar] Some recipes might have the vegetables tossed in ground peanuts.
[src:batak-cuisine/acar] *Acar* is commonly served as a condiment to be eaten with a main course, such as *martabak*, *nasi goreng* (fried rice), satay, and almost all varieties of *soto*.
[src:batak-cuisine/acar] Just like common pickles, the sour taste of *acar* is meant to freshen up a meal, especially fishy dishes such as *ikan bakar* (grilled fish) or rich and oily dishes such as mutton satay to neutralize the fat.
[src:batak-cuisine/acar] In Indonesia, acar is commonly made from small chunks of cucumber, carrot, shallot, bird's eye chili and occasionally pineapple, and marinated in a sweet and sour solution of sugar and vinegar.
[src:batak-cuisine/acar] Some households add lemongrass or ginger to spice it up.
[src:batak-cuisine/acar] It is usually used as condiment to accompany grilled foods such as satay.
[src:batak-cuisine/acar] Nevertheless, *acar* can also be consumed as a whole, complete dish.
[src:batak-cuisine/acar] For example, *ikan acar kuning* is a fish dish (gourami, mackerel or tilapia) served in *acar* pickles of cucumber, carrot, shallot and red chili, mixed with yellow spice paste made of ground turmeric, candlenut, ginger, garlic and shallot.
[src:batak-cuisine/acar] It is known as *atjar* (pickle) in Dutch cuisine, derived from Indonesian *acar*, since the Netherlands and Indonesia share colonial ties.
[src:batak-cuisine/acar] Variations of Malaysian and Singaporean *acar* include *acar awak* or Nyonya *acar* and Malay *acar*.
[src:batak-cuisine/acar] *Acar awak* is more elaborate, containing additional vegetables such as eggplants as well as aromatic spices in the pickling mix.
[src:batak-cuisine/acar] The salad has also been adopted into Thai cuisine, where it is called *achat* (Thai: อาจาด, pronounced [ʔāː.t͡ɕàːt]).
[src:batak-cuisine/acar] It is made with cucumber, red chilies, red onions or shallots, vinegar, sugar and salt.
[src:batak-cuisine/acar] It is served as a side dish with the Thai version of satay (Thai: สะเต๊ะ).
[src:batak-cuisine/acar] With Indian and Malay slaves initially brought by the British Empire, *atchar* became a favourite condiment in South Africa.
[src:batak-cuisine/acar] The local variation is usually made with green mangoes.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-cuisine] A variety of Acehnese food is cooked with curry or coconut milk, which is generally combined with meat such as buffalo, beef, goat meat, lamb, mutton, fish, or chicken.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-cuisine] Several Aceh dishes can trace their origins to India, such as roti canai, which was derived from Indian flatbread.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] The **Acehnese** (Acehnese: *Ureueng Acèh* [uˈrɯ(ə̯)ŋ aˈcɛh], Husaini: *Ureuëng Atjèh*, Jawoe: اورڠ اچيه‎; Indonesian: *Orang Aceh*), also written as **Achinese**, are an Austronesian ethnic group native to Aceh, a province on the northernmost tip of the island of Sumatra in Indonesia.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] The area has a history of political struggle against the Dutch colonial rule.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] The vast majority of Acehnese people are Muslims.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] The Acehnese people are also referred to by other names such as **Lam Muri**, **Lambri**, **Akhir**, **Achin**, **Asji**, **A-tse** and **Atse**.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Their language, Acehnese, belongs to the Aceh–Chamic group of Malayo-Polynesian of the Austronesian language family.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] The Acehnese were, for a time, partially Hinduised, as evident from their traditions and the many Sanskrit words in their language.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Trade with the Islamic world resulted in the Islamization of the population and gradually displaced older religions practiced by the Acehnese.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] As a result, the Acehnese have been Muslims for many centuries.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] The estimated number of Acehnese ranges between 3,526,000 people to 4.2 million people.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Traditionally, Acehnese are agriculturists, metal-workers and weavers.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Traditionally matrilocal, their social organisation is communal.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] They live in *gampôngs*, which combine to form districts known as *mukims*.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] The golden era of Acehnese culture began in the 16th century, along with the rise of the Islamic Aceh Sultanate and later reaching its peak in the 17th century.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Generally, the Acehnese people are regarded as conservative adherents to the Islamic faith and also as militant fighters against the colonial conquest of the Portuguese Empire and the Dutch Empire.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Aceh came to international attention as being the hardest-hit region of the 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake with 120,000 people dead.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Archaeological evidence show that the earliest inhabitants of Aceh were from the Pleistocene age, where they lived in the west coast of Aceh (Langsa and Aceh Tamiang Regency region) and exhibited Australomelanesoid characteristics.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] They mainly relied on a diet of seafood, including various types of shellfish, as well as land animals.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] The inhabitants are known to have used fire and practiced rituals of burial.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] The migration of the modern-day indigenous tribes, such as the Mantr people and the Lhan people (Proto-Malay), as well as the Chams, Malays and Minangkabau people (Deutero-Malay) who arrived later, formed the *pribumi* dwellers of Aceh.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Foreign ethnic groups, especially Indians, as well as a small amount of Arabs, Persians, Turks, and Portuguese also compromise the ancestry of the Acehnese people.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] The strategic position of Aceh in the northern tip of the Sumatra island for thousands of years has allowed the region to become a haven for trade and inter-marriage of various people groups, namely those involved in the sea trade route from the Middle East to China.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] The geographic gap between other Chamic languages and Acehnese may have led to influence on Indochinese speakers of Chamic languages from Malay, Khmer, Thai, and Vietnamese over the following two thousand years.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Chinese and Indian sources from 500 CE and onward mention that there was a settlement in northernmost Sumatra (Aceh) which was called P'o-lu.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Many scholars believe that P'o-lu was close to the what is now Banda Aceh.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] These sources also state that the average person wore cotton clothing while the ruling elite wore silk.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] The Chinese annals also claim that the local people were Buddhist.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Acehnese folklore states that the earliest people of Aceh came from indigenous tribes such as the Mante people and the Lhan people.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] The Mante people were a local native group believed to be related to the Batak, Gayonese and Alas people, while the Lhan people are allegedly still related to the Semang people group who had migrated from the Malay Peninsula or Indochina (specifically Champa and Burma).
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Initially, the Mante people settled in Aceh Besar Regency and later began to spread to other regions.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Around the ninth and tenth century there was an influx of Arabian and Persian merchants to the Aceh region.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] When Marco Polo visited the area in 1292, he mentions that some of the port cities and towns had already converted to Islam.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] It is commonly thought that when the Samudera Pasai Sultanate was founded, Islam was fully established in the region.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Nonetheless, it is clear that Islam was a major religion in and around Aceh by the thirteenth century.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] During the decline of the Srivijaya kingdom, it is estimated that a number of Malay people began to migrate to Aceh.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] They then settled down in the valleys of Tamiang River and later became known as the Tamiang people.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] After they were conquered by the Samudera Pasai Sultanate kingdom (1330), only then did they begin to integrate into Acehnese society; although in terms of cultural and linguistic, there are still similarities with the Malay culture.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] By the sixteenth century, Aceh was an important cultural and scholastic Islamic center influential throughout much of Southeast Asia.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Most of the Minangkabau people who migrated to Aceh settled around Meulaboh and Krueng Seunagan valley.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Generally in these fertile areas they manage wet paddy fields and pepper farming, as well as some trading.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] The mixed population of Acehnese-Minangkabau people is also found in the southern region, namely in the areas around Susoh, Tapaktuan and Labuhan Haji.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] There are many who converse daily in both Acehnese language and their own native dialect, the Aneuk Jamee language.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] As a result of the political expansion and diplomatic relations of the Aceh Sultanate with their surrounding region, the Acehnese people were also mixed with the Alas people, Gayonese, Karo people, Nias people and Kluet people.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] The unification of the Acehnese culture that stemmed from various ancestry are primarily in the Acehnese language, religion of Islam and the local customs, as how it was formulated by Sultan Iskandar Muda in the *Adat Makuta Alam*laws, which is well known as "Kanun Mahkota Alam".
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] There are many of those who are of Indian descent in Aceh, which are closely linked to trading and the spreading of Hinduism-Buddhism and Islam in Aceh.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Those who are of Indian descent are mainly Tamils and Gujarati people which are found spread throughout the entire Aceh.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Among some of the Indian people's influence on the Acehnese people includes the cultural aspects and physical attributes of part of the Acehnese people, as well as the variety in Acehnese cuisine that frequently utilizes curry.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Numerous place names of Sanskrit origin (for example, Indrapuri, Aceh Besar) reflects the cultural heritage of Hinduism in the past.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Most of the Arabs that migrated to Aceh came from Hadhramaut, Yemen.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Among the immigrants are those of the Ba Alawi including al-Aydrus (Aidrus, Aydarus), al-Attas, al-Kathiri, Badjubier, Sungkar, Bawazier & al-Habsyi and other clans; all of which are Arabic clans that originated from Yemen.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] They came as ulamas to spread Islam and as traders.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Seunagan district for an instance, is well known to this today for numerous of ulamas of the Sayyid descent, of which the local community would address them with the title *Teungku Jet* or *Habib* as a form of respect.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Similarly, some of the Sultan of Aceh are also descendants of Sayyid.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Many of their descendants today have intermarried with the natives Acehnese people and do no longer bear their clan names.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] There are also those of Persian descent that generally came to spread religion and to trade, while those of Turkish descent generally were invited as ulamas, weapon merchants, military trainers and soldiers of war for the Aceh Sultanate.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] At present, people of Persian and Turkish descent in Indonesia are mostly scattered in Aceh Besar Regency.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Names of Persian and Turkish heritage are still being used by Acehnese people to name their children.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] In fact, the word *Banda* in the name of Banda Aceh city is also a word of Persian language in origin (*Banda* means "port").
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] People of Portuguese descent are found mainly in the Aceh Jaya Regency (northwest section of Aceh).
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Portuguese sailors under the lieutenant leadership of Captain Pinto, were sailing towards Malacca, stopped by and traded there; where some of them remained and settled there.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] History records that this event occurred between 1492 and 1511; of which at that time the area was under the rule of a small kingdom called Lamno, with King Meureuhom Daya as their ruler.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Until this day, some of their descendants can still be seen with European features.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Acehnese belongs to the Chamic languages, a branch of the Malayo-Polynesian languages from the Austronesian languages.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Languages that are closely related with Acehnese are Cham, Roglai, Jarai, Rade, Chru, Tsat, as well as other Chamic languages that are spoken in Cambodia, Vietnam and Hainan.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] There are also loanwords from Mon-Khmer languages, many of which are shared with other Chamic languages and had already been borrowed in the Proto-Chamic, the ancestral proto-language of all Chamic languages.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Vocabulary of the Acehnese language have been enriched by absorption from Sanskrit and Arabic language, especially in the field of religion, laws, governance, warfare, arts and knowledge.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] For centuries, the Acehnese language have also absorbed a lot from the Malay language.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Initially, a group of Chamic languages migrant speakers controlled a small region only, namely Banda Aceh in Aceh Besar Regency.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Marco Polo (1292) states that Aceh at that time consists of 8 smaller kingdoms, with each of them possessing their own language.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] The expansion of power on other coastal kingdoms, especially Pidie, Pasai and Daya, and absorption of their population over time in a period of 400 years, eventually made the language of the Banda Aceh population became dominant in the coastal region of Aceh.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Other native languages speakers were then forced into the interior by the expansion of land for farming by the Acehnese language speakers.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Dialects of the Acehnese language that are found in the Aceh Besar Regency valley are divided into two major groups, namely the Tunong dialect for dialects in the highlands and Baroh dialect for dialects in the lowlands.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Most of the dialects that are used in Aceh Besar Regency and Daya, shows that settlements in that region have existed longer than any other regions.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] There are also many dialects in Pidie Regency, although not as much as in Aceh Besar Regency and Daya.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Dialects on the east coast of Pidie Regency and in southern Daya tend to be more homogeneous, so much so that it is co-related with the migration that came along with the expansion of power of the Aceh Sultanate after the 1500s.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Local government of Aceh, among others through Governor's Decree No.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] 2 of 1990 established the Institute of Acehnese Customary and Culture (Lembaga Adat dan Kebudayaan Aceh, LAKA), with the mandate to develop the customs and norms of the communities and customary institutions in Aceh.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Indirectly, this institution protects the preservation of the Acehnese language because in every cultural and customary activity, the delivery of such activities is carried out in the Acehnese language.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Likewise, the Acehnese language is also commonly used in everyday affairs that are organized by government agencies in Aceh.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Traditional Acehnese dance portrays the heritage culture, religion and folklore of the common folk.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Acehnese dance are generally performed in groups, either in a standing or sitting position, and the group of dancers are of the same gender.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] If seen from the musical standpoint, the dance can be grouped into two types.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] One is accompanied with vocals and physical percussive movements of the dancers themselves, and the other is simply accompanied by an assemble of musical instruments.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Acehnese cuisine is known for its combination of spices just as are commonly found in Indian and Arabic cuisine, such as ginger, pepper, coriander, cumin, cloves, cinnamon, cardamom and fennel.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] A variety of Acehnese food is cooked with curry or curry and coconut milk, which is generally combined with meat such as buffalo, beef, mutton, fish, or chicken.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Several types of traditional recipe use a blend of cannabis as a flavoring spice; such cases are also found in the cuisine of some other Southeast Asian countries, such as Laos.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] However today, those substances are no longer used.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Due to conflict after the Dutch invasion of Aceh, followed by Martial Law in Aceh during the attempt to break away from Indonesia, and the 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake, many Acehnese fled abroad.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] The most significant number of Acehnese can be found in Malaysia and Scandinavian countries, especially Sweden and Norway countries.
[src:batak-cuisine/acehnese-people] Acehnese immigrants also can be found significantly in Australia, United States and Canada.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] The cuisine of Afghanistan is *halal* and uses various herbs and spices including coriander, mint, dill, cumin, cardamom and turmeric as well as locally-grown saffron.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Afghan dishes are typically mild in flavor.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] A variety of rice dishes known locally as 'palao' are prepared with various fruits, nuts and legumes, and combine sweet and sour flavors central to Afghan cuisine.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Dumpling and noodle dishes, meat and vegetable stews, legumes, and kebab dishes make up the bulk of Afghan cuisine.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Rice is a core staple food in Afghan cuisine and the most important part of any meal.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Challow, or white rice cooked with mild spices, is served mainly with *qormas* (*korma*: stews or casseroles).
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Palaw is cooked similarly to challow, but a combination of meat, stock, *qorma*, and herbs are also mixed in before baking, resulting in the elaborate colors, flavors, and aromas from which the rice got its name.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Sometimes caramelized sugar is used to give the rice a rich brown color.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Afghan bread is flat and cooked in a tanoor or tandoor (a vertical ground clay oven).
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] The bread is slapped onto a stone wall to cook.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Tabakhai is a flatbread cooked on a flat upside-down pan.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Known under the name *khameerbob* and often eaten as dumplings, they are rarely served at large gatherings, such as weddings.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] They are instead served on special occasions at home.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Qormah (also spelled "korma" or "qorma") is an onion- and tomato-based stew or casserole usually served with challow rice.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] First, onion is caramelized, for a richly colored stew.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Then tomato is added, along with a variety of fruits, spices, and vegetables, depending on the recipe.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] The main ingredient, which can be meat or other vegetables, is added last.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Afghan kabob is most often found in restaurants and at outdoor street vendor stalls.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Most of the time, it contains lamb meat.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Kabob is made with naan instead of rice.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Customers have the option to sprinkle sumac or *ghore angoor* (dried ground sour grapes) on their kabob.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Pieces of fat from the sheep's tail (*jijeq*) are usually added to the skewers to add extra flavor.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Traditional Afghan kabobs are made with onion juice, lemon, yoghurt, black pepper and sometimes saffron for chicken.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Other popular kabobs include the lamb chop, ribs, *kofta* (ground beef), and chicken.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Chapli kebab, a specialty of eastern Afghanistan, is a patty of minced beef.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] It is a popular barbecue meal in Afghanistan.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] It is prepared flat and round and served with naan.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] The original recipe of chapli kabob dictates a half-meat, half-flour mixture which renders it lighter in taste and less expensive.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] This type of kabob contains herbs and sometimes chilli.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Afghan chicken or *murgh-e* is a classic example of one of the most famous dishes of Afghanistan.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Chicken dishes are usually found in restaurants and at outdoor street vendor stalls.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Unlike in the Indian cooking style, chicken in Afghan cuisine is often used with the intention that it be *halal*.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Cream, butter, and curd are customary ingredients in all chicken recipes, whether served as an appetizer or a main course.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] As a dessert after a meal, most Afghans generally eat fresh fruit.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] For snacks, they may drink tea with something sweet like cakes, cookies or pastries.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] On occasions, they also eat dried fruits which are widely available in every Afghan market.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Chai is tea in Afghanistan, which can either be green or black.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] It is consumed at all times, especially a short time after finishing a meal or with guests during any social gathering.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Most people drink green tea with no sugar.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Doogh (also known by some Afghans as *shomleh* or *shlombeh*) is a cold drink made by mixing water with yogurt and then adding fresh or dried mint.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Some variations of doogh include the addition of crushed or diced cucumber chunks.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] It is the second most widely consumed drink in Afghanistan (the first being tea), especially during lunchtime in summer.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Doogh can be found at almost every Afghan grocery store and is served in restaurants.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] While Afghans have a common cuisine, certain ethnicities form sub-variations of it.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Pashtuns are the largest ethnic group of Afghanistan, constituting about 42% of the country's total population.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] A major dish in Pashtun culture are rosh (cooked lamb and mutton with no spices) and sohbat, found at traditional gatherings and events.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Other major Pashtun dishes include lamb-skewered *sajji* and *chapli kebab*.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] The name *dampukht* stands for steamed meat, and *khaddi kebab* is the Afghan shashlik, which is grilled on an open fire, on a spit.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Although it differs between regions, Pashtun cuisine is meat-heavy and often includes caramelized rice.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] For example, the dish known as *bolani* in the north and east is often called *borogyen* in the south and west of Afghanistan.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Common summer beverages include *shlombeh*, a drink consisting of liquid yogurt, mint, and cucumber.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] *Sher yakh* is a sweet ice-like product.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] The Hazara people in central Afghanistan (in the region of Hazarajat) and western Pakistan (Balochistan province) have their own fare.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] The Hazaragi cuisine shares some similarities with neighboring regional cuisines, so it is mainly influenced by Central Asian, Persian, and South Asian cooking.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] However, cooking methods vary in some of the dishes of these neighboring cuisines.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Traditionally, dinners are served on a tablecloth on the floor, which is called the *dastarkhan*.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Meals are normally eaten with the right hand.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] After a meal, tea with dessert is served.
[src:batak-cuisine/afghan-cuisine] Serving tea and white sugared almonds (called *nuql*) is customary during Afghan festivals.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Each region in Africa has developed its own distinctive culinary practices, shaped by local ingredients, colonial history and trade.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] In **West Africa,** for example, dishes often feature rice, millet, and beans complemented by spicy stews made with fish, meat, and leafy greens.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The use of chili peppers, peanuts and palm oil is also widespread in this region.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] **Central African** cuisine on the other hand, tends to be simpler and relies heavily on starchy foods such as cassava and plantains, often served with sauces made with peanuts or vegetables.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] In **East Africa**, particularly in countries like Kenya, Tanzania, and Uganda, the cuisine reflects a combination of native agricultural practices and influences from trade routes with India and the Middle East.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Staples such as maize, beans, and rice are commonly consumed along with dishes like Ugali (a maize-based porridge) and sukuma wiki (a dish made from collard greens).
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The coastal areas of East Africa, particularly along the Swahili coast, feature seafood and curries seasoned with spices such as cardamom and cloves, a direct influence of Indian and Arab traders.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] **Southern African** cuisine also displays a blend of indigenous ingredients and colonial influences.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Dishes such as pap (a maize-based porridge) and biltong (a type of sausage) are popular in countries like South Africa, Botswana, and Namibia.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The cuisine is characterized by the use of game meat, maize, and beans, as well as European influences introduced during colonial times.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Traditionally, the various **cuisines of Africa** use a combination of plant-and seed-based ingredients, without having food imported.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] In some parts of the continent, the traditional diet features an abundance of root tuber products.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Africa represents a rich history of adaptation, trade, and resourcefulness. while regional differences are pronounced, the use of local ingredients and traditional cooking techniques remains central to the continent's culinary identity.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Central Africa, East Africa, North Africa, Southern Africa and West Africa each have distinctive dishes, preparation techniques, and consumption modes.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The roots of native African cuisine goes back to thousands of years before the Bronze Age in Northeast Africa, when early civilizations began cultivating grains such as barley and wheat.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Part of North Africa is in the Fertile Crescent where settled agriculture was practiced by the Ancient Egyptians in this area.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Animals such as donkeys and sheep were also domesticated, starting the spread of agriculture to other parts of Africa, notably West Africa.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Although most tribes still lived a simple hunter-gather diet.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Arab explorers- Leo Africanus and Ibn Battuta- provided accounts of African food which they encountered on their travels through sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Most European travelers stayed close to coastal areas until the 19th century.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Many of their diaries also recorded details on foods and crops.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Many staples were introduced later when Africa was colonized by the Europeans.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Foods that are now important parts of African cuisine such as maize and potatoes were not common until the 19th century.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The influence of African food on Caribbean, Brazilian, American Lowcountry cuisine, and Cajun cuisine from Louisiana is seen in rice dishes and green stews like the Afro-Caribbean efo, duckanoo and callaloo.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The vegetable okra, introduced from Africa, is used in classic Louisiana gumbos, and American rice growing in the Carolina.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Lowcountry was influenced by West African techniques of rice cultivation and many slaves hailed from the rice-growing regions of West Africa.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Lowcountry cuisine is still known for its distinctive rice dishes.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Central Africa expands from the Tibesti Mountains in the north to the vast rainforest basin of the Congo River, the highlands of Kivu and the savannah of Katanga.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] This region has received the culinary influence of the Swahilis (culture that evolved via the combination of Bantu, Yemeni, Omani and Indian cultures) during the trans-Saharan slave trade.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Swahili culinary influences can be found in dishes such as mandazi, pilaf rice, kachumbari, sambusa, and kuku paka.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Central African cuisine has also been influenced by the Portuguese, by way of the Kongo and Ndongo Kingdoms.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Salt fish was introduced following trade in the late 17th century, and the Kikongo term for salt fish, makayabu, comes from the Portuguese term bacalhau.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The Portuguese culinary influence is especially prominent in Angola, Sao Tomé and Equatorial Guinea.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Central Africa has also been influenced by the cuisine of the East, West and Southern Africa regions because of their close proximity, e.g. babuté or bobotie is shared with the south, nyama choma with the east and sauce gombo with West Africa.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] In Central Africa, a variety of crops are grown, including yams, cassava, bananas and plantains, sweet potatoes, and cocoyams.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] These crops have become staples in the diet of many people in Central Africa.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Fufu-like starchy foods are usually made from fermented cassava roots, but they can also be made with plantain, corn maize and yam.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Fufu is served buffet-style with grilled meat, fish, stews, greens and piment .
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] A variety of local ingredients are used while preparing other dishes, like spinach stew cooked with tomato, peppers, chilies, onions, and peanut butter.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Eastern central Africa is also one of the few regions in Africa that uses potatoes as one of its main bases, since potatoes grow easily in the region.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Cassava plants are also consumed as cooked greens.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Groundnut (peanut) stew is also prepared, containing chicken, okra, ginger, and other spices.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Beef and chicken are favorite meat dishes, but game meat preparations containing crocodile, elephant, antelope and warthog meats are also served occasionally.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The cuisine of East Africa varies from area to area.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] In the inland savannah, the traditional cuisine of cattle-keeping peoples is distinctive meaning that meat products are generally absent.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Cattle, sheep, pigs and goats were regarded as a form of currency and a store of wealth.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] They are not generally consumed as food.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] In some areas, traditional East Africans consume the milk and blood of cattle, but rarely the meat.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Elsewhere, other Africans are farmers who grow a variety of grains and vegetables.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Maize (corn) is the basis of ugali', the local version of West and Central Africa's fufu.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Ugali is a starch dish eaten with meats or stews.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] In Uganda, steamed green bananas called matoke provide the starch filler of many meals.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Around 1000 years ago, Omani and Yemeni merchants settled on the Swahili Coast.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Middle Eastern influences are especially reflected in the Swahili cuisine of the coast—steamed or cooked rice with spices in Persian style; saffron, cloves, cinnamon and several other spices; and pomegranate juice.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Several centuries later, the British and the Indians came, and both brought with them foods such as Indian spiced vegetable curries, lentil soups, chapattis and a variety of pickles which have influenced various local dishes.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Some common ingredients used in this region include oranges, lemons, limes, chilies, capsicum peppers, maize, tomatoes, and strawberries.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] In the Horn of Africa, the main traditional dishes in Eritrean cuisine and Ethiopian cuisine are tsebhis (stews) served with injera (flatbread made from teff, wheat, or sorghum) and hilbet (paste made from legumes, mainly lentils and fava beans).
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Eritrean and Ethiopian cuisine (especially in the northern half) are very similar, given the shared history of the two countries.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Eritrean and Ethiopian food habits vary regionally.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] In the highlands, injera is the staple diet and is eaten daily among the Tigrinya.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Injera is made out of teff, wheat, barley, sorghum or corn, and resembles a spongy, slightly sour pancake.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] When eating, diners generally share food from a large tray placed in the center of a low dining table.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Many injera are layered on this tray and topped with various spicy stews.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Diners then break into the section of injera in front of them, tearing off pieces and dipping them into the stews.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] In the lowlands, the main dish is akelet, a porridge-like dish made from wheat flour dough.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] A ladle is used to scoop out the top, which is filled with berbere and butter sauce and surrounded by milk or yoghurt.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] A small piece of dough is broken and then used to scoop up the sauce.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The best known Ethiopian/Eritrean cuisine consists of various vegetable or meat side dishes and entrées, usually a wat, or thick stew, served atop injera, a large sourdough flatbread made of teff flour.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] One does not eat with utensils, but instead uses injera to scoop up the entrées and side dishes.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Tihlo, prepared from roasted barley flour, is very popular in Amhara, Agame, and Awlaelo (Tigray).
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Traditional Ethiopian cuisine employs no pork or shellfish of any kind, as they are forbidden in the Jewish and Ethiopian Orthodox Christian faiths.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] It is also very common to eat from the same dish in the center of the table with a group of people.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Somali cuisine varies from region to region and consists of an exotic mixture of diverse culinary influences.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] It is the product of Somalia's rich tradition of trade and commerce.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Despite the variety, there remains one thing that unites the various regional cuisines: all food is served halal.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] There are therefore no pork dishes, alcohol is not served, nothing that died on its own is eaten, and no blood is incorporated.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Varieties of bariis (rice), the most popular being basmati, usually serve as the main dish.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Spices like cumin, cardamom, cloves, cinnamon and sage are used to aromatize these different rice dishes.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] During Ramadan, dinner is often served after Tarawih prayers, sometimes as late as 11 pm.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Xalwo (halwo) or halva is a popular confection served during special occasions such as Eid celebrations or wedding receptions.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] It is made from sugar, cornstarch, cardamom powder, nutmeg powder, and ghee.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Peanuts are also sometimes added to enhance texture and flavor.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] After meals, homes are traditionally perfumed using frankincense (lubaan) or incense (cuunsi), which is prepared inside an incense burner referred to as a dabqaad.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Food and nutrition security in East Africa (Rwanda, Burundi and South Sudan) is a significant issue.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The region has been plagued by drought, conflict and economic instability since the 1990s.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The current situation is characterized by low levels of food availability and high levels of malnutrition among young children.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The solution proposed for this problem is to increase local food production.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] This would be achieved by increasing agricultural productivity by improving soil fertility and water management, which will help farmers grow more crops per year.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] This will also help reduce poverty in the region by providing more employment opportunities for local people.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] In a study of food loss and waste in North Africa, researchers found that the region was wasting about 30% of its food, which is likely to increase as the population continues to grow.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] This waste occurs for a variety of reasons, including lack of refrigeration and storage facilities.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] To solve this issue, the people had to get creative with new dishes and ways of storing food.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The more we looked, the more we found that people were using all parts of plants in some way—the leaves, stems, flowers, fruits and seeds.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] They also used every edible part of animals as well—from fat to bones for making broth or soup.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] North Africa lies along the Mediterranean Sea and encompasses within its fold several nations, including Morocco, Algeria, Libya, Tunisia, and Egypt.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The roots of North African cuisine can be traced back to the ancient empires of North Africa, particularly in Egypt, where many of the country's dishes and culinary traditions date back to African antiquity.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Over several centuries traders, travelers, invaders, migrants and immigrants all have influenced the cuisine of North Africa.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The Phoenicians of the 1st century brought sausages, while the Carthaginians introduced wheat and its by-product, semolina.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The Berbers adapted semolina into couscous, one of the main staple foods.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Olives and olive oil were introduced before the arrival of the Romans.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] From the 7th century onwards, the Arabs introduced a variety of spices, like saffron, nutmeg, cinnamon, ginger and cloves, which contributed and influenced the culinary culture of North Africa.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The Ottoman Turks brought sweet pastries and other bakery products, and from the New World, North Africa got potatoes, tomatoes, zucchini and chili peppers.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] In addition, two completely different dishes may also share the same name (for example, a tajine dish is a slow-cooked stew in Morocco, whereas the Tunisian tajine is a baked omelette/quiche-like dish).
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] There are noticeable differences between the cooking styles of different nations, from the sophisticated, full-bodied flavors of Moroccan palace cookery to the fiery dishes of Tunisian cuisine and the humbler, simpler cuisines of Egypt and Algeria.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The cooking of the Southern Africa region (not to be confused with the country of South Africa) is sometimes called "rainbow cuisine", as the food in this region is a blend of many cultures: indigenous African societies, European, and Asian.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] To understand indigenous African cuisine, it is important to understand the various native peoples of southern Africa.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The indigenous Africans of Southern Africa were roughly divided into two groups and several subgroups.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The largest group consisted of the Bantu-speakers, whose descendants today may identify themselves by various subgroup names such as Ndebele (northern and southern), Shona, Venda, Zulu, Xhosa, Swazi, Sotho, Tswana, Pedi and Tsonga.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] They arrived in the region around 2,000 years ago, bringing crop cultivation, animal husbandry, and iron toolmaking with them.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Hence the Bantu-speakers grew grain crops extensively and raised cattle, sheep and goats.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] They also grew and continue to grow pumpkins, beans, and leafy greens as vegetables.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] A smaller group were the primeval residents of the region, the Khoisan, who some archaeologists believe had lived in the region for at least 10,000 years.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Many descendants of the Khoisan people have now been incorporated into the population of South Africa.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The Khoisan originally were hunter-gatherers (who came to be known as "San" by the Bantu-speakers and as "bushmen" by Europeans).
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] After the arrival of the Bantu-speakers, however, some Khoisan adopted the Bantu-speakers' raising of cattle but did not grow crops.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] People were, in other words, defined to some extent by the kinds of food they ate.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The Bantu-speakers ate dishes of grain, meat, milk and vegetables, as well as fermented grain and fermented milk products.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] While the Khoi-Khoi ate meat and milk and the San hunted wild animals and gathered wild tubers and vegetables.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] In many ways, the daily food of native South African families can be traced to the indigenous foods that their native African ancestors ate.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The Khoisan and Bantu traditionally ate roasted meat, and they also dried meat for later use.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The influence of their diet is reflected in the universal Southern African love of barbecue (generally called in South Africa by its Afrikaans name, a "braai") and biltong (dried preserved meat).
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The traditional beer was ubiquitous in the southern African diet, and the fermentation added additional nutrients to the diet.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] It was a traditional obligation for any family to be able to offer a visitor copious amounts of beer.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Beer brewing was done by women, and the status of a housewife in pre-colonial southern Africa depended significantly on her skill at brewing delicious beer.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Milk was historically one of the most important components of the southern African diet.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Cattle were considered a man's most important possession.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] In order to marry, a man had to compensate his prospective in-laws with a gift of cattle as a dowry for his bride.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] A married man was expected to provide a generous supply of milk to his wife and children, along with meat whenever he slaughtered cattle, sheep or goats.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Because there was no refrigeration, milk was mostly soured into a kind of yogurt.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The young men of the family often took care of the cattle far away from the villages at "cattle posts," and they sent a steady stream of yogurt home on behalf of their fathers.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Today, many South Africans of African origin enjoy drinking sour milk products that are sold in the supermarket, comparable to American buttermilk, yogurt, and sour cream.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] On weekends they will have a "braai", and the meal usually consists of "pap and vleis", which is maize porridge and grilled meat as has historically been done in the region.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The basic ingredients include seafood, meat products (including wild game), poultry, as well as grains, fresh fruits and vegetables.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Fruits include apples, grapes, mangoes, bananas, papayas, avocado, oranges, peaches and apricots.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Desserts may simply be fruit, but there are some more western-style puddings, such as malva pudding, reminiscent of sticky toffee pudding, which was inspired by both British cuisine and Dutch cuisine.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Meat products include lamb, and game like venison, ostrich, and impala.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The seafood includes crayfish, prawns, tuna, mussels, oysters, calamari, mackerel, and lobster.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] There are also several types of traditional and modern alcoholic beverages including many European-style beers.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] A typical West African meal is made with starchy items and can contain meat, fish, as well as various spices and herbs.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] A wide array of staples are eaten across the region, including fufu, banku, kenkey (originating from Ghana), foutou, couscous, tô, and garri, which are served alongside soups and stews.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Fufu is often made from starchy root vegetables such as yams, cocoyams, or cassava, and also from cereal grains like millet, sorghum or plantains.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The staple grain or starch varies between regions and ethnic groups, although corn has gained significant ground as it is cheap, swells to greater volumes and creates a beautiful white final product that is greatly desired.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Banku and kenkey are maize dough staples, and garri is made from dried grated cassavas.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Rice dishes are also widely eaten in the region, especially in the dry Sahel belt inland.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Examples of these include the Senegalese dish thieboudienne also known as benachin or Jollof rice, a pan-West African rice dish similar to Arab kabsah.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Seeds of Guinea pepper (Aframomum melegueta, also called grains of paradise or melegueta pepper), a native West African plant, were used as a spice and even reached Europe, through North African middlemen, during the Middle Ages.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Centuries before the influence of the Europeans, West Africans were trading with the Arab world and spices like cinnamon, cloves, and mint were not unknown, therefore becoming part of the local flavorings.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Centuries later, the Portuguese, French and British influenced the regional cuisines, but only to a limited extent.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Cooking techniques include roasting, baking, boiling, frying, mashing, and spicing.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] A range of sweets and savories are also prepared.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Cooking techniques of West Africa are changing.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] In the past West Africans ate much less meat and used native oils (palm oil on the coast and shea butter in Sahelian regions).
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Baobob leaf and numerous local greens were everyday staples during certain times of the year.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Today the diet is much heavier in meats, salt, and fats.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Many dishes combine fish and meat, including dried and fermented fish.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Flaked and dried fish is often fried in oil, and sometimes cooked in sauce made with hot peppers, onions, tomatoes, various spices (such as soumbala), and water to prepare a highly flavored stew.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] In some areas beef and mutton are preferred, and goat meat is the dominant red meat.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Suya, a popular grilled spicy meat kebab flavored with peanuts and other spices, is sold by street vendors as a snack or evening meal and is typically made with beef or chicken.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] It is common to have a preponderance of seafood, which as earlier stated, is sometimes also mixed with other meat products.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Guinea fowl and chicken eggs are also preferred.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] With regard to beverages, water has a very strong ritual significance in many West African nations (particularly in dry areas) and water is often the first thing an African host will offer their guest.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Palm wine is also a common beverage made from the fermented sap of various types of palm trees and is usually sold in sweet (less-fermented, retaining more of the sap's sugar) or sour (fermented longer, making it stronger and less sweet) varieties.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The exact origins of Bitter Leaf soup appear to be unknown thought it is known to have been prepared and eaten for hundreds of years.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The dish traditionally consists of fish, meat (usually beef), bitter leaves, palm oil, and an array of spices and seasonings.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Shellfish such as shrimp or crayfish are often used alongside fish in the preparation of Bitter Leaf Soup.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] Due to the bitterness of bitter leaf, the bitter leaf is washed thoroughly to diminish the bitterness before being cooked with the rest of the ingredients.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] It is widely consumed in West Africa, especially Nigeria where it is associated with the Igbo people and referred to as Ofe Onugbu.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The Bitter Leaf itself is known scientifically as Vernonia amygdalina and is native to Sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:batak-cuisine/african-cuisine] The bitter taste comes from the alkaloids contained within the plant.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Batak people are majority Christian — unlike neighboring Muslim-majority ethnic groups such as Aceh and Minang — Christian Batak people are not restricted to Islamic halal dietary law.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Many of the Batak's popular meals are made of pork as well as dishes made from unusual ingredients, such as dog meat or blood, however there are also halal batak dishes, mostly chicken, beef, lamb, mutton, and freshwater fishes.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Batak culinary centers are located in towns of Batak highlands, such as the town of Kabanjahe and Berastagi in Tanah Karo area.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] While some towns around the Lake Toba offers freshwater fish dishes such as carp arsik.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] The Northern Sumatra capital of Medan is also a Batak cuisine hotspot where numerous of *Lapo* (Batak eating establishments) can be found, yet the city is also a culinary center of halal Malay Deli, as well as Indian Cuisine and Chinese Indonesian cuisines.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Outside its traditional lands in North Sumatra, Batak cuisine can also be found in *Lapo* in Jakarta, as well as most of the Indonesian major cities.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Batak food is also widely present in Penang, Malaysia due to wide Batak migrant labour population found there.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Cooking traditions in many parts of Sumatra often demonstrates foreign culinary influences; such as Minang, Malay and Acehnese cuisines featuring typical curry-like dishes heavily influenced by Indian and Arabic cuisines.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Batak cuisine however, retain its indigenous Austronesian cooking traditions; such as cooking meats (especially pork) along with its blood.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Similar dish can also be found in Filipino cuisine, such as dinuguan.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] However, since many tribes of the archipelago have converted to Islam, the non-halal dishes such as those using pork, dog meat, or blood, has been abandoned, and now only survive in non-Muslim areas, such as Batak lands.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Regional differences between Batak and Acehnese culinary influences, among others, are characterized by the choice of spices; curry leaves or andaliman.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Coastal Acehnese people using curry leaves (*Murraya koenigii*) as the main spice, while the Batak people prefer andaliman.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Regions that use andaliman as main spices starting from the Gayo highlands in Central Aceh continue to the southeast up to Berastagi in Tanah Karo in North Sumatra.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] The most widely used spice in Batak cuisine is andaliman and *batak onion* (chives), they are commonly used for all types of arsik.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] The most common Batak spicy sauce is called arsik — it is a Batak sauce made from the mixture of andaliman, turmeric, garlic and candlenut.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] There are many unique spices used in Batak cuisine recipes.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Sambal Tuktuk for example use a mixture of andaliman and other spices.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Other spices commonly used in Batak cuisine includes kaffir lime, Indonesian bay leaves, coriander, onion, garlic, chili pepper, pepper, lemongrass, ginger, galangal and turmeric.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] For many centuries Batak tribes has led a relatively isolated way of life and maintained their ancestral belief systems.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] As the result a lot of the indigenous elements of their culture still survive, including their culinary arts.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Today majority of Batak tribes are Christian, for example Batak Toba, Karo, and Pakpak.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Pork and dog meats are commonly consumed.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Dog meat is usually called B1, derived from *biang*, Batak word to refer a dog, while pork is often called B2 from *babi*.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Pork (B2) or dog meat (B1) are usually cooked in its own blood, spiced and seasoned as saksang, or grilled as panggang.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] However, there is also Muslim Batak tribes, such as Mandailing Batak tribe.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] They apply Islamic dietary law which only allows halal food and forbid consumption of pork, dog meat, and blood.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Popular Batak pork dish are saksang, fried cutlets sauteed pork in thick spicy blood sauces and *Babi Panggang Karo* (karo roast pork) — often shortened to BPK — which is locals' favourite and has become nationally famous through *Lapo* Batak restaurants nationwide.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] BPK consists of roasted pork slices with three accompaniments: a bowl of broth made from the essence of boiled pig's bones, a platter of porcine blood cooked with pepper and chili, and a saucer of extra-hot chili sauce.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Another common meat consumed in the Batak cuisine is buffalo meat, beef and chicken.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Manuk Napinadar is a grilled chicken smothered in chicken blood itself, spiced with andaliman and garlic powder.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Ayam Tasak Telu is one of popular chicken dish in Batak cuisine.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Since the Batak tribes live in the interior of North Sumatra, freshwater fish that live in rivers or Lake Toba is commonly consumed by locals.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Carp usually cooked as Arsik or Dengke Mas na Niura, the fish is not cooked, but just seasoned and flavored in heavy spices.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] In addition to carp, catfish and tilapia are also consumed, usually cooked as Na Tinombur.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Batak dishes sometimes use unusual meats such as dog meat (B1 or "biang" ) cooked as saksang or roasted as panggang.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] One unusual notorious dish is Pagit-pagit that has distinctly pungent aroma.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Another exotic and rare ingredients is *kidu*.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] It is the Karo word for white, plump grubs or insect larvae found in sugar palm trees.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] The kidu-kidu sausages are named as such because they look similar to the grubs.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] The grubs are lightly fried to make the outer skin crispy while keeping the inner part juicy, and then briefly cooked in a boiling arsik sauce.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] For the Batak community, *tuak* (palm liquor) is not just for drinking binges.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] The beverage is mandatory at celebrations, and drinking *tuak* has become something of a tradition.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] It is a popular traditional alcoholic beverage made from palm wine.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] It is made by fermenting the *enau* sap.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Batak *Lapo Tuak* is a drinking establishment dedicated to serve this traditional alcoholic beverage.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] North Sumatra is also known as coffee production area in Indonesia.
[src:batak-cuisine/batak-cuisine] Coffee variants such as Mandheling is those coffee beans grown in North Sumatran Mandailing region.
